WEBVTT

00:01.512 --> 00:03.421
<i>Previously on</i> Madam Secretary...

00:03.422 --> 00:05.017
Jareth and I broke off the engagement.

00:05.018 --> 00:07.485
We've been compromised.
Initiate evacuation

00:07.486 --> 00:08.611
<i>procedure Delta.</i>

00:08.612 --> 00:10.097
<i>The ambassador may have
been hacked by GRU.</i>

00:10.098 --> 00:11.365
<i>Nafisa Samadi's disappeared.</i>

00:11.366 --> 00:13.667
<i>Her Russian contact
has also gone missing.</i>

00:13.668 --> 00:15.169
It was the Taliban.

00:15.170 --> 00:18.004
The Taliban were tipped off
by someone on our side.

00:20.174 --> 00:22.809
(BIRDS CHIRPING,
DOG BARKING IN DISTANCE)

00:23.477 --> 00:24.912
- Ah.
- Morning.

00:24.913 --> 00:26.547
When did you get home?

00:26.548 --> 00:27.915
Oh, about half an hour ago.

00:27.916 --> 00:29.917
But I'm just here to take a shower,

00:29.918 --> 00:32.186
then I got to head
right back over there.

00:32.186 --> 00:34.555
- Well, did you get any sleep at all?
- Absolutely.

00:34.556 --> 00:37.158
I crashed for at least 20 minutes

00:37.159 --> 00:39.660
on the couch in the office.

00:39.661 --> 00:41.529
I'm gonna make you breakfast.

00:41.530 --> 00:44.064
- You don't... (GROANS)
- You have to eat.

00:44.065 --> 00:47.268
I am not going to the
nursing home alone.

00:47.269 --> 00:49.904
All those dirty old men? Forget it.

00:49.905 --> 00:51.272
I'll be one of them.

00:51.273 --> 00:54.041
Yeah, but you'll be mine. (CHUCKLES)

00:54.042 --> 00:55.409
Oh.

00:55.410 --> 00:58.445
- No word yet on Nafisa?
- No.

00:58.446 --> 01:00.514
But intelligence finally
combed through all the data

01:00.515 --> 01:02.416
from the leak at the Kabul embassy.

01:02.417 --> 01:04.285
Uh, the report came out last night.

01:04.286 --> 01:06.086
I know... it was my bedtime reading.

01:06.087 --> 01:07.321
Plenty of hacked e-mails

01:07.322 --> 01:09.223
revealing the safe house location,

01:09.224 --> 01:12.159
but nothing about Nafisa's identity.

01:12.160 --> 01:14.895
She must have been burned
by another source.

01:14.896 --> 01:16.430
The most obvious explanation is

01:16.431 --> 01:19.466
their asset, Osip Bakunin,
was a double agent.

01:19.467 --> 01:20.501
Huh.

01:20.502 --> 01:22.770
- STEVIE: Hey, you guys up?
- Yeah.

01:22.771 --> 01:23.737
And decent?

01:23.738 --> 01:25.773
We're in here. Come on in.

01:25.774 --> 01:28.042
- Hi, babe.
- Sorry to...

01:28.043 --> 01:30.544
bust in at the crack of dawn,
but I've actually been trying

01:30.545 --> 01:32.880
to catch you together,
and, believe it or not...

01:32.881 --> 01:35.400
We haven't been in the same room together
for three days? Yeah, we're aware.

01:35.401 --> 01:37.051
- Yeah.
- Work stuff.

01:37.052 --> 01:39.319
Yeah, it's... I get it. Um...

01:40.254 --> 01:42.957
Okay, so there's not
really an easy way to...

01:42.958 --> 01:44.225
to say this.

01:44.226 --> 01:46.526
I'm sitting down.

01:47.995 --> 01:49.862
Um...

01:52.433 --> 01:54.501
Jareth and I broke up.

01:54.502 --> 01:57.004
- Oh, honey, I'm so sorry.
- Oh. What happened?

01:57.005 --> 01:59.906
Lots of stuff, but mainly just...

02:00.641 --> 02:02.710
I don't know, it wasn't right.

02:02.711 --> 02:05.446
We were really trying
to make it work, and...

02:05.447 --> 02:09.149
I guess he just decided
to stop... trying,

02:09.150 --> 02:10.550
so...

02:10.551 --> 02:12.419
Oh, baby, I'm so sorry.

02:12.420 --> 02:14.388
(WHISPERS): Goodness.

02:14.389 --> 02:16.590
Oh.

02:16.591 --> 02:19.627
I'm gonna make breakfast.
I'm gonna make your favorite.

02:19.628 --> 02:22.897
- Banana pancakes wrapped in bacon.
- No, Mom, it's okay.

02:22.898 --> 02:25.733
I got to... I have to get to
work, but, uh, I'll be fine.

02:25.734 --> 02:28.035
I just hope you guys
aren't too disappointed.

02:28.036 --> 02:30.437
You know? I-I just know how much

02:30.438 --> 02:33.007
you liked him, and... and you were...

02:33.008 --> 02:34.608
boot buddies and everything, and...

02:34.609 --> 02:35.843
We're over him already.

02:35.844 --> 02:37.978
- (CHUCKLES)
- If <i>you're</i> over him.

02:37.979 --> 02:40.180
Well, yeah, I've-I've stopped...

02:40.181 --> 02:43.083
bursting into tears every time
I pass a relationship landmark,

02:43.084 --> 02:45.319
so that's...

02:45.320 --> 02:48.054
something.

02:49.490 --> 02:53.227
Maybe you're ready to make the list.

02:53.228 --> 02:55.596
List of all the things

02:55.597 --> 02:59.366
that you secretly hate about Jareth.

02:59.367 --> 03:00.434
That's not very productive, is it?

03:00.435 --> 03:02.135
Well...

03:03.137 --> 03:06.006
Okay. So, um...

03:06.007 --> 03:09.276
well, he used to call
washcloths "flannels"

03:09.277 --> 03:11.645
- Well, that's...
- That's... Mm.

03:11.646 --> 03:15.916
I mean, he did... he did clip
his toenails into the sink.

03:15.917 --> 03:17.651
(BOTH GROANING)

03:17.652 --> 03:19.753
That's disgusting.

03:19.754 --> 03:22.256
- HENRY: Yes, I'm throwing up.
- (MOCK RETCHING)

03:22.257 --> 03:25.225
Okay, I see how this
could be... helpful.

03:25.226 --> 03:27.628
It's time-tested.

03:27.629 --> 03:29.730
Yeah.

03:29.731 --> 03:32.199
Um, I got to...

03:32.200 --> 03:33.701
Aw, honey.

03:33.702 --> 03:35.635
Thanks, Pop.

03:38.005 --> 03:40.373
I love you guys.

03:41.275 --> 03:44.010
ELIZABETH: Love you, sweetheart.

03:44.678 --> 03:46.780
You sure <i>you're</i> okay?

03:46.781 --> 03:48.849
He broke up with <i>her?</i>

03:48.850 --> 03:51.051
(SCOFFS) Jareth who?

03:51.052 --> 03:53.120
NAFISA (ON VIDEO): <i>My name</i>

03:53.121 --> 03:55.723
is Nafisa Samadi.

03:55.724 --> 03:58.692
I am an agent of the CIA,

03:58.693 --> 04:01.628
sent by the corrupt
American government

04:01.629 --> 04:04.031
to spy on the Afghan people.

04:04.032 --> 04:06.000
As a prisoner of the Taliban,

04:06.001 --> 04:08.535
my captors have demands for my return:

04:08.536 --> 04:11.739
$100 million...

04:11.740 --> 04:14.975
and the release
of six Taliban fighters

04:14.976 --> 04:17.411
currently being held
in Parwan Detention Center.

04:17.411 --> 04:20.481
Ebadullah Gulbaz, Abdul Sadat...

04:20.482 --> 04:22.282
It was uploaded an hour ago

04:22.283 --> 04:23.884
somewhere in the Wardak Province.

04:23.885 --> 04:26.653
(SIGHS): Media will run
wild with the CIA angle.

04:26.654 --> 04:29.523
Nafisa's cover was as
an English teacher in Kabul.

04:29.524 --> 04:32.426
The press will have a trail to
follow to Chindawal High School.

04:32.427 --> 04:35.129
But that doesn't change the
fact that the Taliban knows

04:35.130 --> 04:37.898
exactly who she is and how
much she's worth to us.

04:37.899 --> 04:40.768
We need to get her back
as quickly as possible.

04:40.769 --> 04:42.102
HENRY: Then I think

04:42.103 --> 04:43.804
we should consider paying the ransom.

04:43.805 --> 04:45.506
RUSSELL: The United States government

04:45.507 --> 04:48.342
does not give in to extortion
demands from terrorists.

04:48.343 --> 04:50.110
I understand the policy, Russell.

04:50.111 --> 04:52.679
If we pay, Americans abroad will
have a target on their backs,

04:52.680 --> 04:54.314
we'll be working
against our own interests

04:54.315 --> 04:57.117
by potentially funding the very
groups we're trying to destroy.

04:57.118 --> 04:58.098
What's your quibble?

04:58.099 --> 04:59.816
The world is not so black
and white anymore.

04:59.817 --> 05:03.223
Americans have always
been taken by radical groups.

05:03.224 --> 05:06.560
Only now, when we don't pay,
they're more likely to be murdered.

05:06.561 --> 05:09.496
And their execution videos
become a recruiting tool.

05:09.497 --> 05:12.733
France, Italy, Germany,
Spain, Switzerland,

05:12.734 --> 05:14.201
South Africa, they all pay...

05:14.202 --> 05:16.937
directly or by proxy.

05:16.938 --> 05:18.372
And their people come back alive.

05:18.373 --> 05:21.508
Yes, we are holding the
line for a principle,

05:21.509 --> 05:23.277
but we're doing it alone.

05:23.278 --> 05:24.812
And Americans are dying.

05:24.813 --> 05:27.314
ELIZABETH: We all know
how complicated it is.

05:27.315 --> 05:29.716
It's just...

05:29.717 --> 05:33.987
a rethink on policy might not
be helpful at this juncture.

05:33.988 --> 05:36.423
DALTON: I appreciate your
alternative view, Henry,

05:36.424 --> 05:39.426
but it's a nonstarter.

05:39.427 --> 05:41.962
The United States does not
negotiate with terrorists.

05:41.963 --> 05:44.565
And that's a policy I'm
not prepared to end today.

05:44.566 --> 05:46.500
Let's talk about other options.

05:46.501 --> 05:48.769
There's a SEAL team in
Bagram that's ready to go.

05:48.770 --> 05:50.237
All we need is a location.

05:50.238 --> 05:52.396
Our contacts on the ground
have yielded nothing.

05:52.397 --> 05:54.341
Well, maybe a reward for information

05:54.342 --> 05:55.642
would shake something loose.

05:55.643 --> 05:57.111
Have Rewards for Justice

05:57.112 --> 05:59.279
authorize up to $5 million
for any Intel

05:59.280 --> 06:02.949
that leads to a favorable resolution.

06:05.052 --> 06:06.653
Are you okay?

06:06.654 --> 06:08.956
'Cause I can easily
switch over to wife mode

06:08.957 --> 06:11.758
- if you want to rant.
- (CHUCKLES) I'm good, but thanks.

06:11.759 --> 06:14.761
I mean, I get why we all
need to be on the same page.

06:14.762 --> 06:17.394
- It's just a military option is expensive
- I know.

06:17.395 --> 06:19.466
And risky. We'll be spending
more than the ransom demand,

06:19.467 --> 06:21.735
- putting more American lives at risk...
- It's complicated.

06:21.736 --> 06:23.834
Do you know that that
same Taliban faction

06:23.835 --> 06:27.908
released a French hostage yesterday?
An aid worker. Gisele Durand.

06:27.909 --> 06:30.241
And even though the
French are denying it,

06:30.242 --> 06:32.643
the rumor is they paid
ten million euros.

06:32.644 --> 06:34.912
Any chance we could talk to her?

06:34.913 --> 06:36.914
If she crossed paths with Nafisa,

06:36.915 --> 06:39.884
she might know something that could
help us nail down a location.

06:39.885 --> 06:42.319
Well, yeah, I can...
schedule a debrief

06:42.320 --> 06:44.255
- as soon as possible.
- Okay.

06:44.256 --> 06:45.556
Okay.

06:45.557 --> 06:47.358
Okay.

06:47.359 --> 06:48.825
Bye.

06:49.460 --> 06:50.861
♪

06:50.862 --> 06:52.463
MATT: <i>I know you're interviewing</i>

06:52.464 --> 06:54.699
candidates for your old
job as policy advisor.

06:54.700 --> 06:56.467
I have someone I'd like to pitch.

06:56.468 --> 06:58.836
Almost at the end
of the process, but sure.

06:58.837 --> 07:00.671
Ashley Haines. We went
to Yale together.

07:00.672 --> 07:03.040
She's been a fellow at the
Talmadge Institute for five years.

07:03.041 --> 07:05.776
But she reached out when she heard
there was an opening over here.

07:05.777 --> 07:07.578
She's tired of just
talking about policy

07:07.579 --> 07:09.714
- and is ready to help implement it?
- Exactly.

07:09.715 --> 07:11.015
She's Uber-smart,

07:11.016 --> 07:14.051
socially committed,
and has a terrific arm.

07:14.052 --> 07:15.619
- State softball team.
- State softball team. With Daisy out,

07:15.620 --> 07:17.388
we need help at third
base... send me a résumé.

07:17.389 --> 07:19.156
Thanks, buddy.

07:19.157 --> 07:22.026
♪

07:22.027 --> 07:23.260
(BELL DINGS)

07:23.261 --> 07:26.363
- Good morning, ma'am.
- Morning.

07:26.364 --> 07:28.532
Uh-oh, this doesn't look
like a baby announcement.

07:28.533 --> 07:29.853
Daisy's at two centimeters.

07:29.854 --> 07:31.789
Which is like nowhere, apparently.

07:31.790 --> 07:33.290
She's eating spicy foods,

07:33.291 --> 07:34.792
- <i>(CHUCKLES)
- taking lots of baths.</i>

07:34.793 --> 07:36.293
They're supposed to be jump-starters.

07:36.294 --> 07:38.329
All things I didn't know
before this morning.

07:38.330 --> 07:40.464
Yeah, those final days are the worst.

07:40.465 --> 07:43.600
Nature's way of curing
your fear of childbirth.

07:43.601 --> 07:45.736
Hey, any ideas

07:45.737 --> 07:47.237
- on Nafisa Samadi?
- Hmm, yes.

07:47.238 --> 07:49.340
After talking it over,
we think our best option

07:49.341 --> 07:51.241
- is Pakistan.
- Hmm.

07:51.242 --> 07:53.010
No, n-now, I know
what you're gonna say.

07:53.011 --> 07:55.546
The ISI is untrustworthy at
best, deceptive at worst.

07:55.547 --> 07:57.614
Any information they
give us is suspect,

07:57.615 --> 07:59.350
and any intelligence we give them

07:59.351 --> 08:02.319
ends up in the hands of our enemies.

08:02.320 --> 08:04.021
- But...
- Yeah. You, uh...

08:04.022 --> 08:06.724
well, you might want to rethink
your use of the phrase

08:06.725 --> 08:08.692
- "best option." Yes.
- "Best option."

08:08.693 --> 08:11.495
But you have given me an idea.

08:11.496 --> 08:13.497
Call the Pakistani embassy.

08:13.498 --> 08:16.233
Get me an urgent meeting
with Sameet Akhtar.

08:16.234 --> 08:18.168
He's the deputy chief of mission.

08:18.169 --> 08:20.971
Off the books.

08:20.972 --> 08:23.040
(LIGHT KNOCKING)

08:23.041 --> 08:24.174
Yeah.

08:24.175 --> 08:26.243
Interpol just sent over security video

08:26.244 --> 08:28.011
taken near where Nafisa
was meeting with Bakunin.

08:28.012 --> 08:31.152
It shows a black van
speeding north at 1:00 a.m.

08:31.153 --> 08:33.057
DMITRI: It's registered
to a Russian corporation.

08:33.058 --> 08:34.725
A front for the GRU.

08:34.726 --> 08:38.091
Now they're lending them
vehicles for their kidnappings?

08:38.092 --> 08:39.960
Any Intel on Bakunin's whereabouts?

08:39.961 --> 08:42.496
- Not yet.
- Because he's back home in Mother Russia,

08:42.496 --> 08:44.498
being rewarded by his
handlers for handing over

08:44.499 --> 08:46.633
a CIA agent to the Taliban.

08:46.634 --> 08:49.102
There was nothing in his profile
to indicate he was sympathetic

08:49.103 --> 08:52.074
- to the current administration.
- Well, then maybe they leveraged him

08:52.075 --> 08:53.507
and he's back home in prison.

08:53.508 --> 08:55.409
Either way, the guy clearly
wasn't cut out to be an asset.

08:55.410 --> 08:57.849
- It was a screw up.
- Nafisa sat across the table from him,

08:57.850 --> 08:58.783
looked into his eyes,

08:58.784 --> 09:00.652
and believed he could be trusted.

09:00.653 --> 09:01.786
If a seasoned agent

09:01.787 --> 09:03.088
can be fooled, then anyone can.

09:03.089 --> 09:04.355
Our job is to find her...

09:04.356 --> 09:06.391
let's stay focused on that.

09:06.392 --> 09:08.793
Okay?

09:08.794 --> 09:10.929
I think the last time
we saw each other,

09:10.930 --> 09:13.665
you were digging your
car out of a snowbank

09:13.666 --> 09:15.533
at the top of the Dorah Pass.

09:15.534 --> 09:17.602
I appreciate you
pitching in with a shovel.

09:17.603 --> 09:20.105
It's all part of the unwritten rule...

09:20.106 --> 09:22.874
be willing to help out a fellow spy

09:22.875 --> 09:24.342
whenever possible.

09:24.343 --> 09:27.110
You are here for a favor.

09:27.979 --> 09:31.883
An American woman was
kidnapped in Afghanistan.

09:31.884 --> 09:35.220
We want to get her back
as quickly as possible.

09:35.221 --> 09:39.758
I need you to convince President
Sahi to intercede on our behalf.

09:39.759 --> 09:41.559
It will be expensive.

09:41.560 --> 09:44.662
Money isn't changing hands.

09:44.663 --> 09:47.699
If we financially compensate Pakistan,

09:47.700 --> 09:49.167
there's a good chance

09:49.168 --> 09:51.402
the cash will be passed along

09:51.403 --> 09:54.672
to the Taliban through weapons or aid.

09:54.673 --> 09:58.109
Ah, such sticklers, you Americans.

09:58.110 --> 10:02.346
It's your Puritan heritage.

10:03.681 --> 10:05.150
Look, it would be one thing

10:05.151 --> 10:07.028
if this kidnapped woman
were an aid worker

10:07.029 --> 10:09.788
- or a journalist, but she is CIA.
- She was in Kabul teaching

10:09.789 --> 10:12.590
English literacy to high schoolers.

10:12.591 --> 10:14.524
- Elizabeth.
- (CHUCKLES)

10:20.965 --> 10:22.567
(SIGHS)

10:22.568 --> 10:24.736
This is an opportunity

10:24.737 --> 10:27.639
for Pakistan to stand on
the world stage with us

10:27.640 --> 10:29.741
and condemn terrorism.

10:29.742 --> 10:34.278
Yes, well, we've been looking
for a way to do that.

10:38.016 --> 10:40.384
I will do my best.

10:41.119 --> 10:44.222
Hey. Can you guys
check me on something?

10:44.223 --> 10:45.825
All right, look,

10:45.826 --> 10:47.492
she's clearly reading
from a scripted statement,

10:47.493 --> 10:48.593
and there's no way to tell

10:48.594 --> 10:49.894
where she's being held.

10:49.895 --> 10:51.569
So maybe I'm looking too hard

10:51.570 --> 10:53.838
for clues, but look at her hands.

10:53.839 --> 10:55.940
You see how they're moving
on the table? And then her eyes.

10:55.941 --> 10:58.877
It's almost imperceptible,

10:58.878 --> 11:01.079
how they're glancing to the side.

11:01.080 --> 11:03.114
It's not CIA tap code.

11:03.115 --> 11:04.883
DMITRI: Maybe...

11:04.884 --> 11:06.785
maybe Morse.

11:06.786 --> 11:11.556
You know, I-I remember there's a
story from the Vietnam War era.

11:11.557 --> 11:14.058
There was a P.O.W.,
Jerry Denton, who...

11:14.059 --> 11:16.227
was forced to film a piece
telling the American government

11:16.228 --> 11:18.897
that prisoners in Hanoi
were being treated well.

11:18.898 --> 11:20.932
He used Morse code.

11:20.933 --> 11:24.001
He blinked out the word "torture."

11:30.375 --> 11:33.411
She's trying to send us a message.

11:33.412 --> 11:40.787
Subtitle sync and corrections by
<font color="#FF0000"><b>awaqeded</b></font> for <font color="#FF0000"><b>www.addic7ed.com.</b></font>

11:43.491 --> 11:45.660
Anybody home?

11:45.661 --> 11:47.928
(SIGHS)

11:47.929 --> 11:50.196
Anybody?

11:53.379 --> 11:54.847
STEVIE: Mom?

11:54.848 --> 11:57.884
Yeah, yeah, yeah!
I'm down here in the kitchen!

11:57.885 --> 11:59.686
Come have dinner with me?

11:59.687 --> 12:01.354
- Please?
- Hi.

12:01.355 --> 12:02.555
Hi.

12:02.556 --> 12:04.524
Dad just texted me from work,

12:04.525 --> 12:06.259
asking how I was doing.

12:06.260 --> 12:07.961
It was very sweet.

12:07.962 --> 12:12.031
Oh, uh, also, Jason
is having dinner at Piper's.

12:12.032 --> 12:13.132
Again?

12:13.133 --> 12:14.634
Well, Piper's mom said that he's

12:14.635 --> 12:16.002
the son she never had, so...

12:16.003 --> 12:18.404
But he's the son I did have.

12:18.405 --> 12:19.806
I'd like him to start

12:19.807 --> 12:21.607
hanging out here more.

12:21.608 --> 12:23.009
Well,

12:23.010 --> 12:25.310
I'm happy to see you.

12:26.045 --> 12:28.847
What did Jareth do?

12:30.450 --> 12:33.453
It's creepy how you do that, Mom.

12:33.454 --> 12:36.456
Okay, so I'm scrolling
through Facebook,

12:36.457 --> 12:37.623
- just to relax, you know.
- Uh-huh.

12:37.624 --> 12:40.360
And I see that Jareth has posted

12:40.361 --> 12:42.228
some pictures
from his grandma's birthday.

12:42.229 --> 12:43.796
This is the first time
he's posted anything

12:43.797 --> 12:44.764
since we broke up.

12:44.765 --> 12:46.466
- He's smiling.
- Yeah!

12:46.467 --> 12:48.234
He's smiling.

12:48.235 --> 12:50.370
Really, really big. And he's wearing

12:50.371 --> 12:52.705
the Ted Baker shirt I got
him for his birthday.

12:52.706 --> 12:55.074
I mean, just, like, h-how can you end

12:55.075 --> 12:57.510
- a two-year relationship
- I-I don't know.

12:57.511 --> 12:59.445
And then smile big,

12:59.446 --> 13:01.781
wearing the shirt that I bought him

13:01.782 --> 13:03.082
like it's nothing?

13:03.083 --> 13:04.317
Here's the thing,

13:04.318 --> 13:07.286
you're gonna have to unfriend Jareth.

13:07.287 --> 13:08.654
I can't do that.

13:08.655 --> 13:10.256
Well, you're never gonna be happy

13:10.257 --> 13:12.625
as long as you're staring
at pictures of him

13:12.626 --> 13:15.995
smiling too big in
shirts you bought him.

13:15.996 --> 13:18.297
(SIGHS)

13:18.298 --> 13:20.633
There's no closure, baby,
if he never goes away.

13:20.634 --> 13:21.634
(SIGHS)

13:21.635 --> 13:24.437
It just sucks.

13:24.438 --> 13:26.472
Yeah.

13:26.473 --> 13:28.740
It does.

13:30.977 --> 13:32.879
And...

13:32.880 --> 13:35.214
it's gonna suck for a while.

13:35.215 --> 13:37.250
You can't let yourself do things

13:37.251 --> 13:39.951
that are just gonna make it suck more.

13:41.587 --> 13:43.056
Yeah, I know.

13:43.057 --> 13:44.957
But I still have to go
to his apartment

13:44.958 --> 13:46.993
and pack up all my stuff,

13:46.994 --> 13:48.194
leave my key.

13:48.195 --> 13:50.463
Not without me, you don't.

13:50.464 --> 13:52.732
We're gonna do it together.
Friday night.

13:52.733 --> 13:54.534
Chimichangas after. Don't argue.

13:54.535 --> 13:56.801
I won't.

14:00.073 --> 14:01.341
Morning. What do you got?

14:01.342 --> 14:03.143
DYLAN: This is it. It was Morse code.

14:03.144 --> 14:04.911
This is what Nafisa
was trying to communicate.

14:04.912 --> 14:08.114
Yeah, it turns out she wasn't
using her eyes, just her hands.

14:08.115 --> 14:09.449
The question is, what does it mean?

14:09.450 --> 14:11.318
And they're not
geographical coordinates.

14:11.319 --> 14:13.787
It could be part of an address
or-or a phone number.

14:13.788 --> 14:15.188
But then what's the "M" for?

14:15.189 --> 14:17.190
She risked her life
to get us this message.

14:17.191 --> 14:19.125
Let's have Interpol run a search.

14:19.126 --> 14:21.061
Let's get it out to the
entire intelligence community.

14:21.062 --> 14:22.628
We've got to figure this out.

14:24.931 --> 14:26.232
Morning.

14:26.233 --> 14:28.801
(CLEARS THROAT)

14:30.337 --> 14:32.038
Stevie,

14:32.039 --> 14:34.407
that, uh,

14:34.408 --> 14:37.277
history of the DAR you put
together for my upcoming speech

14:37.278 --> 14:38.612
was, uh...

14:38.613 --> 14:40.780
was very helpful.

14:40.781 --> 14:42.882
Who told you?

14:42.883 --> 14:44.884
What?

14:44.885 --> 14:47.220
About my breakup. Was it my mom?

14:47.221 --> 14:48.989
ADELE: I didn't mean
to speak out of turn.

14:48.990 --> 14:50.490
I just thought we should
all be sensitive.

14:50.491 --> 14:51.691
No, no, it-it's okay.

14:51.692 --> 14:53.793
And I'm fine.

14:53.794 --> 14:55.095
Of course you're fine.

14:55.096 --> 14:56.730
And in a few months,
you're gonna be saying

14:56.731 --> 14:58.064
this was the best thing

14:58.065 --> 14:59.232
that ever happened to you.

14:59.233 --> 15:02.801
Well, I don't know about that.
(CHUCKLES)

15:05.438 --> 15:07.073
Let me tell you a little story.

15:07.074 --> 15:10.176
I was dating this,
uh... this woman once.

15:10.177 --> 15:11.945
A world-class political operative.

15:11.946 --> 15:14.381
We were just at the point
where I needed to figure out

15:14.382 --> 15:16.416
if we were going to the next level.

15:16.417 --> 15:18.284
And she went out of town,

15:18.285 --> 15:19.953
and I agreed to watch her dog.

15:19.954 --> 15:22.288
A little teacup... something.

15:22.289 --> 15:23.523
Name of Gigi.

15:23.524 --> 15:26.760
Anyway, one day, I'm
walking Gigi, and she gets

15:26.761 --> 15:28.895
spooked by a cab.

15:28.896 --> 15:31.498
Starts chasing it, yanks
the leash right out of my hand.

15:31.499 --> 15:33.767
I'm running down the
street yelling, "Gigi!

15:33.768 --> 15:35.101
- Come back, Gigi" (BOTH CHUCKLING)

15:35.102 --> 15:37.737
But... she's gone.

15:37.738 --> 15:41.975
Well, my girlfriend came home,
and she was furious.

15:41.976 --> 15:44.144
And after an hour

15:44.145 --> 15:46.913
of her shrieking about my immaturity

15:46.914 --> 15:48.948
and lack of good sense, I finally

15:48.949 --> 15:52.619
got down on one knee and begged her...

15:52.620 --> 15:54.454
to marry me.

15:54.455 --> 15:56.222
Wh...

15:56.223 --> 15:59.259
I was just looking to make it stop.

15:59.260 --> 16:00.593
(LAUGHS) Which proves

16:00.594 --> 16:02.162
she was right... I was not yet

16:02.163 --> 16:03.697
husband material.

16:03.698 --> 16:07.867
But it took six miserable years
of marriage to figure that out.

16:07.868 --> 16:10.136
- (CHUCKLES)
- Anyway, my advice to you

16:10.137 --> 16:12.138
is... don't think of this period

16:12.139 --> 16:15.108
of your life as an engagement
ending... think of it as...

16:15.109 --> 16:17.811
the time you dodged a bullet.

16:17.812 --> 16:19.579
Okay.

16:19.580 --> 16:21.280
Thanks.

16:22.549 --> 16:24.350
Uh, just to confirm, you're
meeting with the secretary

16:24.351 --> 16:27.153
Monday at 3:00 p.m.
Have security call when you're

16:27.154 --> 16:29.180
on your way up, and I will
meet you at the elevator

16:29.181 --> 16:30.054
on the seventh floor.

16:30.055 --> 16:32.492
Okay. Great. Thanks so much.

16:32.493 --> 16:33.960
Bye-bye.

16:33.961 --> 16:36.029
Setting up, uh, interviews
for the policy job?

16:36.030 --> 16:37.197
Uh, yeah.

16:37.198 --> 16:39.132
When's Ashley Haines coming in?

16:39.133 --> 16:41.034
Uh, she's... not.

16:41.035 --> 16:42.235
What? No.

16:42.236 --> 16:44.671
Jay told me that he'd consider her.

16:44.672 --> 16:46.706
Then you have to
take that up with Jay.

16:46.707 --> 16:48.974
(CLICKS TONGUE)

16:54.147 --> 16:56.082
- (ELEVATOR BELL DINGS)
- Good morning, ma'am.

16:56.083 --> 16:58.084
Good morning, Blake. Baby?

16:58.085 --> 16:59.285
I'm sorry?

16:59.286 --> 17:01.187
Has Daisy had the baby?

17:01.188 --> 17:02.388
Oh, no. Not yet.

17:02.389 --> 17:05.391
But Mr. Akhtar, from the
Pakistani embassy, called.

17:05.392 --> 17:06.792
Well, let's get him back.

17:06.794 --> 17:09.095
Uh, apparently, a return
call isn't necessary.

17:09.096 --> 17:12.298
He apologizes but says
he's unable to help.

17:12.299 --> 17:13.833
All right, when are we debriefing

17:13.834 --> 17:16.236
- the French hostage, um, G...
- Uh, Gisele Durand.

17:16.237 --> 17:17.537
- Gisele Durand.
- That's this morning.

17:17.538 --> 17:19.705
Dr. McCord should be here
in about, uh, 15 minutes.

17:19.707 --> 17:21.708
Great. Ask Jay if he'll join us.

17:21.709 --> 17:24.644
Just put on his policy cap,
just for an hour.

17:24.645 --> 17:27.046
Uh, I'm afraid he's already
wearing his, uh,

17:27.047 --> 17:30.116
chief of staff bowler at the
deputy committee meeting

17:30.117 --> 17:32.385
for the disaster relief of Sudan.

17:32.386 --> 17:35.021
When are the new
policy advisor interviews?

17:35.022 --> 17:36.322
That's scheduled for Monday.

17:36.323 --> 17:37.957
(GRUNTS)

17:37.958 --> 17:39.959
Director McCord, a moment?

17:39.960 --> 17:42.695
- Sure.
- One of my contacts in Afghanistan

17:42.696 --> 17:44.663
got back to me with a lead.

17:45.766 --> 17:46.915
Go ahead.

17:46.916 --> 17:49.194
He says he can hook us up with
someone who not only knows

17:49.195 --> 17:51.563
where Nafisa is being
held, but will walk her

17:51.564 --> 17:55.100
out of the Taliban hideout and
deliver her to us personally.

17:55.101 --> 17:57.299
And what does this
magician want in return?

17:57.300 --> 18:00.608
$50 million and amnesty.

18:01.473 --> 18:02.775
Okay, who is this guy?

18:02.776 --> 18:05.878
Akbar Haq Raquib.

18:05.879 --> 18:08.814
The Taliban deputy minister
of foreign affairs.

18:08.815 --> 18:10.149
He says he wants out.

18:10.150 --> 18:11.950
This could be the break that we need.

18:11.951 --> 18:13.619
Or it could be a trap.

18:13.620 --> 18:15.821
Either way, the U.S. doesn't

18:15.822 --> 18:18.157
negotiate with terrorists,
and Raquib more than qualifies.

18:18.158 --> 18:20.692
I understand.

18:20.693 --> 18:22.027
But, you know what,

18:22.028 --> 18:25.263
there's no harm in determining
if the information is solid.

18:26.398 --> 18:27.566
(FOOTSTEPS APPROACHING)

18:27.567 --> 18:28.967
Oh! Uh, good morning, ma'am.

18:28.968 --> 18:30.235
Morning, Matt.

18:30.236 --> 18:33.272
You didn't happen to see
a stray bear claw, did you?

18:33.273 --> 18:35.040
I-I missed breakfast.

18:35.041 --> 18:37.408
- Ma'am, it's me.
- (MICROWAVE BEEPS)

18:38.343 --> 18:39.745
I skipped breakfast in the hopes

18:39.746 --> 18:41.980
that I might <i>find</i> a stray bear claw.

18:41.981 --> 18:43.648
But... (CLEARS THROAT)

18:45.017 --> 18:46.518
Oh, here's one.

18:46.519 --> 18:48.420
Oh, thank you.

18:48.421 --> 18:51.056
Oh, now can you find me
a new policy advisor?

18:51.057 --> 18:54.159
Well, actually, uh, I do have
a friend who's interested

18:54.160 --> 18:56.562
in the position. Ashley Haines.
I think you'd really like her.

18:56.563 --> 18:59.898
Ma'am, the SVTC call
with Gisele Durand is ready,

18:59.899 --> 19:01.700
and Dr. McCord is on his way up.

19:01.701 --> 19:04.703
Okay. Thank you, Maggie.

19:04.704 --> 19:06.271
Sorry.

19:06.272 --> 19:09.408
Give her information to Blake
and he'll set it up, okay?

19:09.409 --> 19:11.143
Thank you, ma'am.

19:11.144 --> 19:13.078
Ms. Durand, thank you so
much for talking with us.

19:13.079 --> 19:15.447
You're very welcome, Madam Secretary.

19:15.448 --> 19:18.784
I am happy to do whatever
I can to help Nafisa.

19:18.785 --> 19:21.220
How long were you two held together?

19:21.221 --> 19:23.889
Just my last few days
before being released.

19:23.890 --> 19:26.291
I am praying you can get her out soon.

19:26.292 --> 19:27.860
We're doing the best we can.

19:27.861 --> 19:30.162
Did the American consul
give you a code to look at?

19:30.163 --> 19:33.699
Yes, uh, the numbers with
the letter "M" in the middle,

19:33.700 --> 19:36.534
but I'm afraid it didn't
mean anything to me.

19:37.769 --> 19:40.405
Uh, if you can tell us anything
else that you remember

19:40.406 --> 19:44.042
about your time in captivity,
uh, no detail

19:44.043 --> 19:45.077
is too small.

19:45.078 --> 19:47.145
They kept us in a windowless room,

19:47.146 --> 19:49.748
usually in the dark,
so I didn't see much.

19:49.749 --> 19:52.084
But...

19:52.085 --> 19:55.220
sometimes we heard things.

19:55.221 --> 19:56.455
Explosions.

19:56.456 --> 19:59.625
You mean...
like there was combat nearby?

19:59.626 --> 20:00.859
I don't know.

20:00.860 --> 20:04.830
We would hear a huge
boom in the distance,

20:04.831 --> 20:07.666
and then nothing.

20:07.667 --> 20:08.934
For hours.

20:08.935 --> 20:10.536
Sometimes not for a day or two.

20:10.537 --> 20:12.970
Then there would be another.

20:13.906 --> 20:16.008
(QUIETLY):
That's controlled detonations.

20:16.009 --> 20:18.277
The code that Nafisa
tapped out had no context

20:18.278 --> 20:19.912
until we put it together
with the sound

20:19.913 --> 20:21.947
that Gisele Durand heard
during her captivity.

20:21.948 --> 20:23.282
Land mines

20:23.283 --> 20:25.851
- going off.
- There are old minefields

20:25.852 --> 20:27.920
in eastern Afghanistan,

20:27.921 --> 20:30.589
some even left over
from the Soviet occupation.

20:30.590 --> 20:31.757
Army Corps of Engineers

20:31.758 --> 20:33.525
has been working for
decades to clear 'em.

20:33.526 --> 20:35.961
HENRY: We believe that Nafisa caught
a glimpse of a control marker

20:35.962 --> 20:39.231
when she was being transported
that indicated a field

20:39.232 --> 20:42.000
200 meters away at a magnetic bearing

20:42.001 --> 20:44.436
- of 130 degrees.
- I'll have the DoD

20:44.437 --> 20:45.871
synthesize the information,

20:45.872 --> 20:48.840
and once we pinpoint
the location we can discuss

20:48.841 --> 20:51.510
- the option of a raid.
- SEAL Team 4 can transport

20:51.511 --> 20:53.577
to Chapman and be
ready to go in 12 hours.

20:54.346 --> 20:56.048
Do we have any other options

20:56.049 --> 20:58.617
- to discuss?
- Well, I've hit a diplomatic

20:58.618 --> 21:01.086
- brick wall.
- HENRY: There is an analyst

21:01.087 --> 21:02.921
in my department who's identified

21:02.922 --> 21:04.256
a possible source in Afghanistan,

21:04.257 --> 21:06.325
one who's intimately
connected with the Taliban

21:06.326 --> 21:07.793
and their methods.

21:07.794 --> 21:10.069
We're still verifying the information.

21:10.070 --> 21:11.496
DALTON: Well, as soon as
you've vetted the contact,

21:11.497 --> 21:14.099
we'll get into it. In the meantime...

21:14.100 --> 21:16.001
it looks like a, uh, military rescue

21:16.002 --> 21:17.302
is the most expedient way

21:17.303 --> 21:19.437
to get Nafisa Samadi back home, so...

21:20.672 --> 21:22.973
...let's do it.

21:29.450 --> 21:31.085
What's the word from the
recon team, Admiral?

21:31.086 --> 21:32.653
Two guards are posted out front.

21:32.654 --> 21:34.054
Our fireteam will take them out

21:34.055 --> 21:36.104
- <i>and breach the door.
- Before we risk any lives,</i>

21:36.105 --> 21:38.864
is there a way to determine for
a fact that Nafisa's in there?

21:38.865 --> 21:40.146
HILL: No visuals,

21:40.147 --> 21:42.882
but IC surveilled a phone
conversation from this location

21:42.883 --> 21:44.951
in which Nafisa's name was mentioned.

21:44.952 --> 21:46.652
Heat signatures indicate
three people congregated

21:46.653 --> 21:49.187
in a back room.
We think she's one of 'em.

21:50.456 --> 21:52.158
Let's go.

21:52.159 --> 21:53.693
Take the house.

21:53.694 --> 21:55.994
Copy. Go, Team.

21:58.331 --> 21:59.498
(GRUNTS)

21:59.499 --> 22:01.534
(GUNFIRE)

22:01.535 --> 22:03.902
(GUNFIRE CONTINUING)

22:06.172 --> 22:07.740
TEAM MEMBER:
Front clear. Two tangos EKIA.

22:07.741 --> 22:09.407
TEAM LEADER: Go, go, go, go!

22:10.609 --> 22:12.778
(RAPID GUNFIRE)
(SHOUTING IN DISTANCE)

22:12.779 --> 22:14.412
Go!

22:21.153 --> 22:22.855
HENRY: Where is she?

22:22.856 --> 22:25.390
(GUNFIRE CONTINUING)

22:27.159 --> 22:28.461
Room two clear.

22:28.462 --> 22:30.829
(HELICOPTER BLADES
WHIRRING IN DISTANCE)

22:32.264 --> 22:34.566
RUSSELL: Come on, come on.

22:35.935 --> 22:38.136
It's a torture room.

22:39.972 --> 22:42.974
TEAM MEMBER:
Sir, I think I found something.

22:47.113 --> 22:49.981
That's Nafisa.

22:50.750 --> 22:51.917
What's next?

22:51.918 --> 22:53.219
It's possible we could track them

22:53.220 --> 22:54.620
if they're still in country.

22:54.621 --> 22:57.189
Possible but not likely.

22:57.190 --> 22:59.091
Henry, where are we on your informant?

22:59.092 --> 23:01.460
Well, my guys have
confirmed he's legitimate,

23:01.461 --> 23:03.195
but it's... complicated.

23:03.196 --> 23:05.398
He's close enough that
he would have been read in

23:05.399 --> 23:07.533
to Nafisa's current
location. And he claims

23:07.534 --> 23:09.402
he could walk her out
and deliver her right to us.

23:09.403 --> 23:11.837
Anyone that close would have
to be a member of the Taliban.

23:11.838 --> 23:13.139
RUSSELL: Yeah, I suspect that's why

23:13.140 --> 23:15.541
Henry's saying it's complicated.

23:15.542 --> 23:18.077
It's Akbar Haq Raquib.

23:18.078 --> 23:20.679
HILL: You're suggesting
that we engage the services

23:20.680 --> 23:22.319
of a Taliban minister?

23:22.320 --> 23:24.617
HENRY: I'm suggesting
that we take advantage

23:24.618 --> 23:26.685
of a loophole.
He's looking to leave the group.

23:26.686 --> 23:28.821
How much does he want for Nafisa?

23:28.822 --> 23:30.222
$50 million. And amnesty.

23:30.223 --> 23:31.590
Oh, is that all?

23:31.591 --> 23:33.626
Wh-What about a Domino's franchise,

23:33.627 --> 23:35.861
- get him started in his new home?
- Look, we're talking about

23:35.862 --> 23:37.763
someone who could give us intelligence

23:37.764 --> 23:40.433
that would be impossible
for us to gather otherwise.

23:40.434 --> 23:41.667
True.

23:41.668 --> 23:44.503
But... he could also take our money

23:44.504 --> 23:46.338
and form his own terrorist faction.

23:46.339 --> 23:48.207
Nixon paid airline hijackers.

23:48.208 --> 23:50.242
Jimmy Carter unfroze eight billion

23:50.243 --> 23:52.244
in Iranian assets during

23:52.245 --> 23:54.346
- the embassy crisis.
- That was before 9/11.

23:54.347 --> 23:56.248
I just have to ask...
is holding to the letter

23:56.249 --> 23:58.150
of this policy more important

23:58.151 --> 23:59.952
than saving citizens that it was

23:59.953 --> 24:01.053
designed to protect?

24:01.054 --> 24:03.622
DALTON: I understand your frustration.

24:03.623 --> 24:05.958
But as commander in chief,

24:05.959 --> 24:07.526
I can't, on the one hand,

24:07.527 --> 24:11.097
ask our military and
intelligence communities to risk

24:11.098 --> 24:13.632
their lives in pursuit of these
criminals, and with the other

24:13.633 --> 24:16.734
potentially fund attacks against them.

24:18.637 --> 24:21.739
Let's keep looking.

24:28.147 --> 24:30.014
Hey.

24:32.184 --> 24:34.485
I could have used
a little help in there.

24:35.387 --> 24:37.156
Well, I'm not gonna support

24:37.157 --> 24:40.592
the abandonment of a
policy that I agree with.

24:42.161 --> 24:44.864
15 years ago it could have
been me in Nafisa's position.

24:44.865 --> 24:47.566
I was in Iraq when John
Marino was kidnapped.

24:47.567 --> 24:50.970
In 1997, Conrad was
stationed in Beirut.

24:50.971 --> 24:54.037
None of us are armchair
warriors, Henry.

24:54.038 --> 24:58.578
We all know that there are
real, real-life consequences

24:58.579 --> 24:59.695
to holding the line.

24:59.696 --> 25:01.275
And yet, if the worst
had happened in Iraq

25:01.276 --> 25:03.816
and you'd been taken, I can
tell you without hesitation

25:03.817 --> 25:05.685
that I would have paid the ransom.

25:05.686 --> 25:07.453
Somehow I would have found a way.

25:07.454 --> 25:09.022
Yes, and if, God forbid,

25:09.023 --> 25:11.891
your brief time on the
ground in Pakistan with José

25:11.892 --> 25:13.593
hadn't had a happy ending,

25:13.594 --> 25:15.795
and someone had come to me
and said, "I can get him out.

25:15.796 --> 25:17.230
I can bring him home," well, then

25:17.231 --> 25:18.531
I would have moved heaven and Earth

25:18.532 --> 25:20.600
to make that happen.

25:20.601 --> 25:23.670
But that's my heart, Henry.

25:23.671 --> 25:26.839
That's why policy is written
in the cold light of day.

25:26.840 --> 25:30.476
Handing over millions of dollars

25:30.477 --> 25:32.712
to the people that I
was fighting against,

25:32.713 --> 25:34.847
that wouldn't have been what I wanted.

25:34.848 --> 25:37.216
And yet you and Conrad are fine
handing over millions of dollars

25:37.217 --> 25:38.985
to an informant with some details

25:38.986 --> 25:41.220
- about Nafisa's whereabouts.
- Because that person

25:41.221 --> 25:43.381
- If it goes through rewards for Justice.
- wouldn't be a terrorist.

25:43.382 --> 25:44.649
You're certain about that.

25:44.650 --> 25:46.594
Or do you think it's possible

25:46.595 --> 25:49.420
that during the time this
program has been in existence,

25:49.421 --> 25:52.123
money might have gone to a wrong guy?

25:52.124 --> 25:54.249
- I mean...
- Yes. Yeah, I know.

25:54.250 --> 25:57.362
I know. It's complicated.

25:57.363 --> 25:59.330
I got to go back to work.

25:59.331 --> 26:01.966
And by the way,

26:01.967 --> 26:06.336
policy can be rewritten
in the cold light of day.

26:13.051 --> 26:16.128
- Hey, do you have Ashley Haines' résumé?
- Yeah.

26:16.129 --> 26:17.430
Why?

26:17.431 --> 26:18.976
Matt pitched her to the secretary,

26:18.977 --> 26:20.043
I'm supposed to get her information,

26:20.044 --> 26:21.282
but Matt's not here,

26:21.283 --> 26:23.122
so I just thought...

26:23.123 --> 26:25.757
I'm sensing none of this
is okay with you. Okay.

26:27.994 --> 26:30.162
What about asking India

26:30.163 --> 26:32.465
to remove non-tariff trade
barriers that block Pakistan

26:32.466 --> 26:34.837
from doing more pharmaceutical
business in the area?

26:34.838 --> 26:39.599
India considers Pakistani visa
restrictions a security issue.

26:39.600 --> 26:41.494
You can add it to the wish list,

26:41.495 --> 26:43.541
but it's too big of an ask right now.

26:43.542 --> 26:44.881
MATT: Since we're on the subject

26:44.882 --> 26:46.716
of Pakistan, um,

26:46.717 --> 26:50.086
I spoke to a friend of mine
from my mother's mosque.

26:50.087 --> 26:52.655
Guy's uncle is pretty
tight with President Sahi

26:52.656 --> 26:54.190
from their university days.

26:54.191 --> 26:58.561
Now, word is, an ISI agent
was captured in India

26:58.562 --> 27:01.664
almost ten years ago, Maarif Baqri.

27:01.665 --> 27:03.400
Now, it turns out he

27:03.401 --> 27:06.002
and President Sahi are cousins.

27:06.003 --> 27:09.939
Now, the family matriarch
is dying and is, uh,

27:09.940 --> 27:14.044
looking to say good-bye to
her nephew one last time.

27:14.045 --> 27:16.346
Sahi's been using back channels,

27:16.347 --> 27:20.116
trying to get India to cut him
loose, but so far no dice.

27:20.117 --> 27:21.918
So your idea is that we could

27:21.919 --> 27:23.753
put pressure on India to release him.

27:23.754 --> 27:26.156
And they're so grateful

27:26.157 --> 27:27.557
to get this one guy back,

27:27.558 --> 27:29.359
they agree to leverage
the Taliban on our behalf?

27:29.360 --> 27:31.861
Doesn't that seem somewhat naive?

27:31.862 --> 27:35.532
Well, it's a, it's an
unspoken exchange of favors,

27:35.533 --> 27:37.133
no money involved.

27:37.134 --> 27:39.235
- A loophole.
- Yeah.

27:39.236 --> 27:42.872
But how are we gonna get the
Indians to release Baqri?

27:42.873 --> 27:45.442
I haven't worked out that part yet.

27:45.443 --> 27:46.976
Yeah, well, that's a very big part.

27:46.977 --> 27:49.412
If you'd come to me beforehand,

27:49.413 --> 27:51.381
we could have worked out
a genuine proposal.

27:51.382 --> 27:52.882
I don't know what you're
hoping to accomplish,

27:52.883 --> 27:54.584
but not for the first time today,

27:54.585 --> 27:57.854
you're wasting the secretary's time.

27:57.855 --> 27:59.656
Okay, I think it's a
good time to take ten.

27:59.657 --> 28:02.024
(CLEARS THROAT) Let's chat.

28:05.495 --> 28:08.731
So is there something going on
that I should know about?

28:08.732 --> 28:10.934
Matt's been bypassing
the chain of command.

28:10.935 --> 28:12.635
I'll take care of it.

28:12.636 --> 28:15.004
Okay. Maybe, uh,

28:15.005 --> 28:18.073
in a more appropriate fashion.

28:19.008 --> 28:20.543
Sorry, ma'am.

28:20.544 --> 28:22.245
I'm just, you know, uh,

28:22.246 --> 28:25.048
still working the kinks out.

28:25.049 --> 28:27.349
No. I-I get it.

28:28.618 --> 28:33.356
You know, when I'd been
at CIA for about...

28:33.357 --> 28:35.959
I don't know, five years,
I was promoted

28:35.960 --> 28:37.293
to task force leader.

28:37.294 --> 28:39.729
That meant that I oversaw
a small department.

28:39.730 --> 28:41.631
I already knew most of the agents.

28:41.632 --> 28:45.802
And they were all very smart,

28:45.803 --> 28:48.938
talented people, great at their jobs.

28:48.939 --> 28:52.342
So I decided that I would stand back

28:52.343 --> 28:54.878
and let them do their work.

28:54.879 --> 28:58.414
I'd help out where I could but
otherwise leave them to it.

28:58.415 --> 29:00.683
And how'd that go?

29:00.684 --> 29:02.685
Huge disaster.

29:02.686 --> 29:04.888
No one knew what was expected of them,

29:04.889 --> 29:06.623
or what the boundaries were.

29:06.624 --> 29:09.092
Everyone was miserable.

29:09.093 --> 29:10.493
And in the end,

29:10.494 --> 29:13.563
I realized that, smart and
talented as they were,

29:13.564 --> 29:16.699
they still wanted a leader,
so I had to give myself

29:16.700 --> 29:18.568
permission to lead.

29:18.569 --> 29:20.670
Yes, ma'am.

29:20.671 --> 29:22.238
I understand.

29:22.239 --> 29:26.042
And I like Matt's crazy idea.

29:26.043 --> 29:28.877
Think you would, too, if you
weren't so pissed at him,

29:30.680 --> 29:35.484
That's why I'm tasking you
with making it work.

29:38.922 --> 29:40.657
TV REPORTER: In other news
under the Capitol dome,

29:40.658 --> 29:42.292
the House Armed Services Committee

29:42.293 --> 29:43.726
met with the top army generals

29:43.727 --> 29:46.228
about the army's tactical
modernization...

29:52.001 --> 29:54.436
(SIGHS)

29:56.472 --> 29:57.640
You wanted to see me?

29:57.641 --> 30:00.043
Yeah, uh, close the door.

30:00.044 --> 30:02.711
- Okay.
- Have a seat.

30:08.151 --> 30:09.852
Uh, look.

30:09.853 --> 30:12.822
I wanted to, uh, apologize

30:12.823 --> 30:14.524
for losing my cool

30:14.525 --> 30:16.259
in the staff meeting. That was wrong.

30:16.260 --> 30:18.895
You had a bad day.

30:18.896 --> 30:20.597
No.

30:20.598 --> 30:22.365
You did an end run around
me to the secretary

30:22.366 --> 30:24.400
about your friend Ashley,
and that ticked me off.

30:24.401 --> 30:26.736
If you had come to me,
I would have told you

30:26.737 --> 30:28.905
that I did look at her
résumé, and while she has

30:28.906 --> 30:30.139
a lot of great qualities,
she just didn't rise

30:30.140 --> 30:31.574
to the same level of expertise

30:31.575 --> 30:33.142
and experience as the
other five candidates.

30:33.143 --> 30:34.811
The secretary and I

30:34.812 --> 30:36.446
were in the break room together.

30:36.447 --> 30:39.315
I-I honestly didn't think
it was that big of a deal.

30:39.316 --> 30:41.751
Well, it was.

30:41.752 --> 30:44.554
Look, a week ago, you told me
I needed to step up if I wanted

30:44.555 --> 30:46.589
to do this job, and, as
tough as it was to hear,

30:46.590 --> 30:48.258
I appreciated the advice.

30:48.259 --> 30:49.759
But I don't think
either of us realized

30:49.760 --> 30:51.661
that meant me acting like your boss.

30:51.662 --> 30:53.796
Outside of here? I'm your buddy.

30:53.797 --> 30:57.132
In here? Your boss.

30:57.834 --> 30:59.369
Copy.

30:59.370 --> 31:01.271
You need to.

31:01.272 --> 31:02.839
Because if you go around me again...

31:02.840 --> 31:05.141
Unemployed buddy. I got it.

31:05.142 --> 31:07.442
Good.

31:08.945 --> 31:11.014
Also, I think I figured out

31:11.015 --> 31:14.683
how to make your crazy
Pakistan idea work.

31:16.819 --> 31:20.056
I called my counterparts in
India, and they were emphatic.

31:20.057 --> 31:22.325
They won't just give
Maarif Baqri to Pakistan

31:22.326 --> 31:24.294
without something in return,
so we started thinking about

31:24.295 --> 31:26.296
- what they might want.
- What they might want. And ever since

31:26.297 --> 31:28.498
India agreed to stricter
carbon emission protocols,

31:28.499 --> 31:30.533
they've been desperate

31:30.534 --> 31:33.770
- for clean, cheap, energy sources.
- Mostly solar panels.

31:33.771 --> 31:35.571
Solar panels, but guess what.

31:35.572 --> 31:37.073
Surprise, surprise,
China's gouging them.

31:37.074 --> 31:38.908
But then I remembered Rafaeli Solar.

31:38.909 --> 31:42.011
Yeah, after they lit up that
Lebanese refugee camp for us,

31:42.012 --> 31:44.480
we basically told them they
had a return favor coming.

31:44.481 --> 31:46.582
So I arranged for some
cheap loans for India

31:46.583 --> 31:48.484
through U.S. banks,
and they agreed to a contract

31:48.485 --> 31:50.253
with Rafaeli to build
these solar fields

31:50.254 --> 31:51.654
- in Andhra Pradesh for half - Half.

31:51.655 --> 31:53.022
What the Chinese are charging.

31:53.023 --> 31:54.691
And in exchange they'll release Baqri.

31:54.692 --> 31:56.959
- JAY: Okay, well, they're willing
- MATT: Sh...

31:56.960 --> 31:58.695
- to release him and it will...
- Yeah.

31:58.696 --> 32:00.330
- Coincidentally be around the same time
- Coincidentally.

32:00.331 --> 32:01.564
That these solar deals get made.

32:01.565 --> 32:02.965
Publicly, they'll say

32:02.966 --> 32:04.367
that Baqri was cooperating
with the government,

32:04.368 --> 32:05.601
and they're, you know,

32:05.602 --> 32:07.270
JAY AND MATT: commuting
his sentence in return.

32:07.271 --> 32:09.572
But I know what you're thinking:
How do we get the Pakistanis

32:09.573 --> 32:11.941
to keep up their end of
this unsigned agreement?

32:11.942 --> 32:14.243
The details of which no one
is willing to spell out,

32:14.244 --> 32:16.512
and most importantly,
aren't enforceable.

32:16.513 --> 32:17.780
So we were hoping...

32:17.781 --> 32:19.115
- That you...
- Might have...

32:19.116 --> 32:21.951
- JAY: The answer to that.
- MATT: An idea.

32:21.952 --> 32:24.087
Blake, can you get me...

32:24.088 --> 32:26.588
Sameet Akhtar. Yes, ma'am.

